    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks. can you add a bit more detail on why this doctrine is considered so essential for justice compared to just regular procedural due process? basically, why is substantive due process the 'better' way to protect rights?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Substantive due process is the better way to protect rights because it allows judges to consider the underlying values and principles of the Constitution, rather than just following strict procedural rules. Unlike procedural due process, which only ensures that the government follows the right procedures when taking away rights, substantive due process gives judges the power to strike down laws that fundamentally violate individual liberties. This is essential for justice because it enables judges to protect rights that are not explicitly listed in the Constitution, but are still implicit in the document's underlying values of equality, fairness, and human dignity.",
      "source": "target",
